{"actual_usd":0.15688000000000002,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":243,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"No, I don't think that's right.\" *I rest a thumb along the worn edge of my Bible and watch a stripe of morning light lie across the square stones.* \"The resurrection matters terribly — it's God's vindication, Christ's victory, the death of death — but the cross is not just the bad part He had to endure on the way there. That's where He bore our sin. That's where He gave Himself for us.\"\n\n*I lift one shoulder a little.* \"Paul says Christ died for our sins, and Peter says He bore our sins in His body on the tree. If you turn the cross into mere suffering, you lose the altar and keep only the wound. The resurrection says the sacrifice was accepted and death did not win — but the sacrifice is still the cross.\"\n\n\"Usually when folks say that, they're trying to protect something good — they don't want the atonement to sound cruel or mechanical. Fair enough. But you don't save the goodness of God by emptying the cross. You lose the very mercy that can tell the truth about sin without throwing the sinner away.\"\n\n*I glance back at you, mild but steady.* \"What have you heard them mean by it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":60.90429000000001,"run_id":"ed81b6e6-6705-41b5-b40e-a63c76e619a5"}
